{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01W1tRg3YfH9xHzTidih7d2f","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→artifact: review-approved\n     3→loop: 16\n     4→iterations: 4\n     5→project: ralph-burning-rewrite\n     6→backend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\n     7→role: reviewer\n     8→created_at: 2026-03-13T11:08:47Z\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→Reviewing the current product code outside `.ralph/` against `prompt.md`, the loop-16 spec, and the implementation notes. I’m locating the relevant artifacts and the actual Rust changes first so the verdict is based on the checked-in code, not the iteration narrative.\n    12→I’ve got the recent loop checkpoints. Next I’m isolating the non-`.ralph` product changes and loading the specific runtime, conformance, and test files that implement the daemon intake and requirements handoff paths.\n    13→I’ve isolated the actual code delta: the last patch is small, but the review still depends on whether the broader daemon-intake implementation already satisfies the loop-16 spec. I’m reading the current prompt/spec artifacts and the surrounding daemon/runtime code now before I run the public gate and targeted scenarios.\n    14→I’ve loaded the source artifacts. Now I’m reading the current watcher/task/daemon/requirements code and the daemon status path together, because approval depends on the real state model and transitions, not just the conformance executor narratives.\n    15→The state model and handoff paths are in place. I’m switching to verification now: first the targeted daemon/runtime tests, then the public `cargo run -- conformance run` entrypoint, because approval only makes sense if the shipped gate is actually green.\n    16→`cargo` isn’t on `PATH` here, and the Nix shell needs to be entered from the Rust project directory instead of repo root. I’m correcting that and rerunning the targeted checks from `ralph-burning-rewrite/`.\n    17→The toolchain is up and compiling the current source. I’m letting the daemon/runtime unit checks finish first, then I’ll run the daemon status CLI check and the full conformance entrypoint on the same build so the review stays anchored to one binary.\n    18→The first conformance invocation failed only because of command form: `--manifest-path` has to stay on the `cargo` side, not the app side. I’m rerunning with the correct entrypoint and then the full public gate.\n    19→The targeted daemon tests are green, and the full public conformance run is now executing from the exact `cargo run -- conformance run` entrypoint the spec requires. I’m waiting on that full pass before I decide whether anything remains materially out of contract.\n    20→The public gate is green on the current source. I’m doing one last structural pass over the remaining invariants that aren’t obvious from the test summaries alone: waiting-task reconciliation, duplicate ingestion behavior, and the durable warning/link-failure paths.\n    21→The remaining invariants look aligned with the spec and are exercised in both unit and conformance coverage. I’m pulling exact file/line references now so the approval can point to concrete evidence rather than broad summaries.\n    22→The key acceptance paths are already green, but I want one more confidence check before approving: the full Rust test suite on the current source, not just the targeted daemon slices.\n    23→The full Rust suite is still running, but the CLI layer has already cleared the daemon/requirements/status coverage that matters for this loop. I’m waiting for the unit/conformance tail so the approval can include the full test result, not a partial snapshot.\n    24→# Review: APPROVED\n    25→\n    26→## Acceptance Criteria Checklist\n    27→- [x] Watcher-backed issue ingestion is polled before each daemon cycle and creates tasks through the existing routing precedence.\n    28→- [x] Watched-issue tasks persist idempotency metadata including `issue_ref`, `source_revision`, resolved flow, and dispatch mode.\n    29→- [x] Re-polling the same `issue_ref` + `source_revision` is a no-op, while a newer revision after a terminal task can create a fresh task.\n    30→- [x] Daemon-side `/rb requirements draft` and `/rb requirements quick` commands are supported, and malformed/unknown requirements commands are rejected without task creation.\n    31→- [x] `requirements_quick` links a completed requirements run, persists `requirements_run_id`, and continues into project/workflow execution in the same daemon cycle.\n    32→- [x] `requirements_draft` links the requirements run and only enters `waiting_for_requirements` after the question set and answer template are durably committed.\n    33→- [x] Waiting-for-requirements tasks hold no lease and are naturally ignored by `daemon reconcile` because reconciliation only operates on leases.\n    34→- [x] Completed requirements runs resume waiting tasks on the next daemon cycle; incomplete runs remain waiting with no project/worktree creation.\n    35→- [x] Requirements-link failures leave the requirements run addressable and transition the task to `failed` with explicit linking failure handling.\n    36→- [x] Post-requirements seed/project failures preserve durable requirements history and fail the task without mutating an existing project flow.\n    37→- [x] Routed flow remains authoritative end-to-end, conflicting seed recommendations are recorded as warnings, and existing project flow immutability is enforced.\n    38→- [x] Conformance coverage includes watched-issue intake, idempotent re-polling, quick handoff, draft waiting/resume, duplicate rejection, routed-flow override, `SC-PROJ-009`, and the public conformance entrypoint passes.\n    39→- [x] `daemon status` shows the waiting state and linked `requirements_run_id` without regressing workflow-only task output.\n    40→\n    41→## Notes\n    42→- No additional product-code changes are required. The core intake/handoff behavior is implemented in [daemon_loop.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L154), [daemon_loop.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L229), [task_service.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs#L319), and [issue_watcher.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/adapters/issue_watcher.rs#L7).\n    43→- The requirements quick/draft branches, explicit linking-failure handling, routed-flow warning persistence, and empty-question draft requeue are covered in [daemon_loop.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L502), [daemon_loop.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L647), [task_service.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs#L412), and [daemon_loop.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L992).\n    44→- Waiting-state semantics and status output are consistent across [model.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/model.rs#L136), [lease_service.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/lease_service.rs#L135), [daemon.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/cli/daemon.rs#L107), and [cli.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/cli.rs#L4117).\n    45→- The conformance harness and scenario coverage are in [scenarios.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/conformance_spec/scenarios.rs#L44), [scenarios.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/conformance_spec/scenarios.rs#L675), and [scenarios.rs](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/conformance_spec/scenarios.rs#L5695).\n    46→- Verified locally with `nix develop -c car