{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01MxWXxDKvyZUJNPfq4kaybe","type":"tool_result","content":"---\nartifact: review-feedback\nloop: 16\niteration: 1\nproject: ralph-burning-rewrite\nbackend: codex(gpt-5.4-xhigh)\nrole: reviewer\ncreated_at: 2026-03-13T03:52:28Z\n---\n\nReviewing the current diff against `prompt.md`, the loop-16 spec, and the implementation notes. I’m starting by isolating the product-code changes outside `.ralph/`, then I’ll verify each acceptance criterion against the actual Rust code and tests.\nThe worktree is effectively clean outside `.ralph/`, so I’m treating this as a review of the current committed loop-16 state. Next I’m checking recent git history and the touched runtime/test files to reconstruct the actual implementation delta.\nI’ve isolated the loop-16 product changes. Now I’m reading the daemon/runtime and requirements handoff code together with the new conformance and unit coverage to see whether the new states and transitions actually satisfy the prompt invariants, not just the tests.\nTwo likely gaps are already visible: the quick path appears to stop after requirements generation instead of handing off into project/workflow execution, and the new conformance scenarios mostly assert `daemon status` success rather than the specified behavior. I’m verifying both against the actual dispatch path and line-level code before I write findings.\nI’ve confirmed a more serious contract mismatch: the quick path writes the seed metadata, then marks the task completed without creating or resuming the project workflow, and the waiting-resume path flips back to `workflow` without deriving the completed requirements seed. I’m running a couple of focused checks now to turn that into concrete evidence rather than inference.\nThe local toolchain isn’t on `PATH`, so I can’t use `cargo` directly here. I’m switching to static verification plus direct inspection of the already-built artifacts under `target/` where possible.\nI can execute the already-built binary, so I’m doing an end-to-end daemon cycle in a temp workspace now. That should tell us whether the quick handoff actually creates a project/run or just exits after generating the requirements seed.\nThe binary reproductions exposed two hard failures. A `requirements_quick` watched issue finishes the requirements run but leaves the daemon task in `pending` with no project created, and a `requirements_draft` watched issue fails immediately because the code tries to transition `pending -> waiting_for_requirements`, which the task state machine forbids.\nI’m checking one more edge of the spec surface: malformed requirements commands should fail ingestion, not quietly fall back to normal workflow routing. The parser looks suspicious there, so I’m validating it with the binary.\n# Review: SUGGESTIONS\n\n## Required Changes\n1. **Requirements handoff lifecycle**: integrate the new requirements dispatch modes with the daemon task state machine and the existing project/workflow handoff.\nCurrent: `process_task` routes `requirements_quick` and `requirements_draft` before claim/activate, but the follow-on helpers only allow `active -> waiting_for_requirements` and `active -> completed`. In a temp workspace, a watched issue containing `/rb requirements quick` left the task `pending` with a linked `requirements_run_id` and no project under `.ralph-burning/projects/`; a watched issue containing `/rb requirements draft` failed immediately with `requirements_linking_failed` on `pending -> waiting_for_requirements`.\nExpected: `requirements_quick` must persist the linked requirements run, derive the seed, and continue through project creation/workflow execution in the same daemon cycle. `requirements_draft` must durably enter `waiting_for_requirements`, and when answers are complete the next daemon cycle must derive the seed handoff before any project/worktree mutation.\nReference: loop-16 acceptance criteria for `requirements_quick`, `requirements_draft`, waiting-state invariants, and resume behavior; [daemon_loop.rs#L292](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L292), [daemon_loop.rs#L417](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L417), [daemon_loop.rs#L513](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L513), [task_service.rs#L406](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs#L406), [task_service.rs#L430](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs#L430), [model.rs#L171](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/model.rs#L171), [daemon_loop.rs#L713](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/daemon_loop.rs#L713)\n\n2. **Requirements command ingestion**: separate requirements-command parsing from flow routing and reject malformed requirements commands instead of silently falling back to workflow dispatch.\nCurrent: `parse_requirements_command` only errors on unknown 3-token variants, so malformed input like `/rb requirements` falls through to `DispatchMode::Workflow`. Also, if `/rb requirements quick` is supplied via `routing_command`, the same field is passed into flow resolution and ingestion fails with a routing error instead of entering the requirements path.\nExpected: unknown or malformed requirements commands must fail ingestion with explicit diagnostics and create no task. Valid requirements commands must still honor flow precedence via `/rb flow <flow-id>` over labels over repo default.\nReference: loop-16 acceptance criterion \"Unknown or malformed requirements commands fail ingestion with explicit diagnostics and create no task\"; [watcher.rs#L26](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/watcher.rs#L26), [watcher.rs#L54](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/watcher.rs#L54), [task_service.rs#L347](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/task_service.rs#L347), [routing.rs#L44](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/automation_runtime/routing.rs#L44)\n\n3. **Conformance coverage**: replace the placeholder DAEMON-INTAKE executors with real scenario assertions.\nCurrent: the new feature file describes watcher ingestion, idempotent re-polling, quick/draft handoff, duplicate rejection, and routed-flow override, but the registered scenario executors just run `daemon status` and assert success. `./target/debug/ralph-burning conformance run --filter DAEMON-INTAKE-003` passes even though the quick handoff behavior above does not satisfy the spec.\nExpected: conformance must actually create watched issues/tasks, run daemon cycles, and assert the durable task/project/requirements state required by each DAEMON-INTAKE scenario, while retaining the `SC-PROJ-009` fixture repair.\nReference: loop-16 acceptance criterion \"Add conformance coverage ... and require `cargo run -- conformance run` to pass end-to-end afterward\"; [daemon_issue_intake.feature#L22](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/tests/conformance/features/daemon_issue_intake.feature#L22), [scenarios.rs#L5524](/root/new-ralph-burning/ralph-burning-rewrite/src/contexts/conformance_spec/scenarios.rs#L5524)","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0145Rc2QGKK9EbsU232znhmJ","session_id":"788958e9-d311-45c0-a75a-a22258565011","uuid":"656fde21-fbc6-429a-87b9-862f2010117c"}
